      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nAs we saw earlier, both the *Yupana* and the abacuses developed in China (Zhongguo 中國) and Japan (Nippon koku or Nihon koku, 日本国) can be understood as tools that reflect our hands.\n\nVimos cómo trabajar con el método **Yupana Inka Tawa Pukllay** (<htcite0>). Con base en este conocimiento, reflexione:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1bb0274d-dc51-4740-ac62-4d157b06ad88",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Yupana (Addition)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: I have seen this before</b><br /><br />How can knowledge of addition using the Yupana help you perform additions using the abacuses?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_comparing",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Common points\n\nLet's begin by making some comparisons. First, recall a line from the *Yupana* in **Table 1** and then observe, in **Figure 1**, images of the abacuses we will be working with.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"yupana0\" class=\"tawapukllay\"><tr><th colspan=\"4\"><i>Yupana</i></th></tr> <tr id=\"tf1\"><td id=\"tc1f1\"><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_center\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_bottom\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc2f1\"><span class=\"dot three_dot_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_up\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_center\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc3f1\"><span class=\"dot two_dot_bottom\"></span> <span class=\"dot two_dot_up\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc4f1\"><span class=\"dot dot_center\"></span></td></tr></table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Representation of a line of the <i>Yupana</i> according to Poma de Ayala (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8'); return false;\">Prem, Dhavit, <htdate0>, pp. 355</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('f5b74f18-0bc4-46d2-8a5c-64dd80b74dd1'); return false;\">Poma de Ayala, Felipe Guaman, <htdate1>, pp. 361 - 362</a>). CSS inspired by <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('48dd9187-7ecc-4f54-a387-d9ecc2497de3'); return false;\">W3School></a> code.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2018",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1615",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"book_navigation\"><tr><td>Soroban (算盤)</td><td>Suanpan (算盤)</td></tr><tr><td><img id=\"imgSoroban\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgSoroban', '0%')\" src=\"\" class=\"imgcenter\" style=\"width: 100%\"/></td><td><img id=\"imgSuanpan\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgSuanpan', '0%')\" src=\"\" style=\"width: 73%\"/></td></tr></table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 1</b>: Abacuses. On the left, we have a Soroban (算盤) by Shigetoshi Oyabu. Maintained by Tohoku University Main Library (<htcite0>). On the right, we have a Suanpan (算盤). © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite1>)</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "8ab7ebef-41db-4f2b-a3e3-3530e7ff29d3",
                     "text": "Shigetoshi Oyabu",
                     "page": "fl. 14",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1842",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "68dfe292-3021-4586-9016-c001cdfdd9d7",
                     "text": "The British Museum",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
