                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Internal divisions\n\nBoth the *Yupana* and the abacuses have similar divisions, which we can understand as representations of our hands.\n\nIn the case of the *Yupana*, the first quadrant on the left would represent one hand with its five fingers. The other three quadrants can be understood as our other hand, but combined in such a way as to represent the five fingers we have.\n\nRegarding the abacuses, the general idea is the same, but there are some details we should highlight. In the case of the Soroban (算盤), the abacus of Japan (Nippon koku or Nihon koku, 日本国), the hand with open fingers is represented by the markers on the upper part — also known as heaven (<htcite0>) —, while the four markers on the lower part — also known as earth (<htcite1>) — would represent the fingers of the other hand.\n\nIn the case of the Chinese abacus, the Suanpan (算盤), we can understand that, in the upper part, there are two hands with their five fingers, while in the lower part, there is a single hand with five fingers.\n\n#### Before adding\n\nWe already know how to add with the *Yupana* and we saw that there are some differences between what the abacuses represent. To make the steps of an addition clearer, in this text we will limit ourselves to adding numbers between zero and nine.\n\nBefore continuing, let's reflect further.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7d978f6b-930f-4aa0-977e-bb0892210acb",
                     "text": "Asian-Pacific Association of Longmount",
                     "page": "pp. 1 - 2",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7d978f6b-930f-4aa0-977e-bb0892210acb",
                     "text": "Asian-Pacific Association of Longmount",
                     "page": "pp. 1 - 2",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Side by side or above and below</b><br /><br />We saw that, although we represent hands in different directions, we can understand that there is a region of the tool representing at least one fully open hand, while there is another region whose elements can be combined until reaching a certain number of fingers.<br /><br />How would you use these representations to add numbers from zero to nine?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
